Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The challenge of instance-dependent label noise (IDN) is increasingly recognized as a critical barrier in real-world deep learning applications, where noisy labels are often generated not just by class-level biases but through complex, feature-driven processes. While recent works have begun to move beyond the classical class-conditional noise assumption (e.g., Paper 3), and some propose multi-source correction frameworks (e.g., Paper 2), they still rely heavily on auxiliary assumptions or clean data priors. Meanwhile, "ambiguation" strategies (e.g., Paper 1) offer a promising direction by relaxing pointwise label supervision into set-valued targets, yet they do not explicitly model the underlying dependency between input features and noise patterns. My key insight is that joint estimation of true labels and DNN parameters under IDN can be made *identifiable*—a rare theoretical guarantee in this domain—if we introduce a meta-level regularization mechanism that alternately optimizes over both the network and latent label distributions using *feature-induced ambiguity sets*. Unlike prior alternating schemes that risk entanglement or degeneracy, our approach leverages a *meta-confidence thresholding* mechanism informed by local feature geometry to dynamically construct superset labels only when uncertainty exceeds a learnable boundary. This creates a feedback loop where the model learns to distrust noisy labels precisely where the feature-to-noise mapping suggests high corruption risk. Crucially, this framework does not require clean validation samples or known noise rates, making it more practical than existing IDN methods. Moreover, by integrating meta-optimization with ambiguity-based learning, we unify two powerful paradigms: robustness via imprecise supervision and adaptivity via bilevel learning. This leads to a provably identifiable joint learning process—one that can disentangle ground-truth signals from complex noise mechanisms purely from observed data.

