  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, 'Variational Belief Aggregation under Instance-Dependent Noise' (VIBRANT), that rethinks label noise correction as a joint Bayesian inference problem over true labels and model parameters under feature-driven corruption. VIBRANT introduces a probabilistic graphical model where the observed noisy label is generated from the true label via an instance-dependent transition matrix parameterized by a neural noise encoder conditioned on input features. Instead of relying on multiple real-world noisy sources, VIBRANT generates synthetic disagreement through stochastic input transformations (e.g., feature dropout, style perturbation) to simulate diverse annotator perspectives from a single label, forming a virtual multi-annotator setup. These perturbed views produce divergent predictions whose agreement patterns inform a variational EM algorithm: in the E-step, we infer a distribution over true labels using amortized inference networks; in the M-step, we update both the classifier and noise encoder by maximizing the expected log-likelihood under the inferred posterior. To enhance identifiability, we introduce a noise-aware contrastive loss that pulls together instances with similar estimated noise transitions in the feature space, encouraging clustering of semantically similar corruptions. Additionally, we derive theoretical conditions under which the true label posterior and noise mechanism are jointly identifiable up to permutation, provided the noise mapping exhibits sufficient diversity across the input manifold. This framework eliminates the need for hand-designed ambiguity rules or meta-thresholds, replacing them with end-to-end differentiable belief updating. VIBRANT advances the state-of-the-art by offering (1) a theoretically grounded, fully probabilistic treatment of IDN, (2) implicit generation of multi-source-like signals without additional labeling effort, (3) improved calibration and uncertainty quantification, and (4) stronger identifiability guarantees than existing alternating schemes. Its implications span safety-critical domains like medical imaging and autonomous perception, where understanding both prediction and noise structure is essential.",
